The findings in this project should also give impetus to further comparative research exploring the long-term consequences of war-time organization. In the last few years, a number of studies have highlighted how the organization of armed groups and opposition movements (in particular, whether they are fragmented and cohesive) shape war-time violence, mediation, and bargaining outcomes, but we know much less about the longer-term effects on the post-war order. 

Though the study initially set out to focus on domestic dynamics, it came to shed light on the importance of considering the transnational and international actors that may shape both war-time organization and the post-war order. While, in this project, I have examined the influence of foreign fighters on rebel movement strength in the case of Chechnya, further research might want to do so in a comparative context. Again, this is a challenging endeavor given data limitations, but as policy concerns with respect to a number of ongoing conflicts (such as Syria and Iraq) should attest to, this is research with clear policy implications. Further research might also want to explore how other external actors-patron states, international organizations, non-governmental organizations-influence post-war states' (including de facto states') state-building capacities. This kind of research is of interest to the scholarly community, but of great interest to policy-makers and other stakeholder working on, in, and with post-war and de facto states.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>66EF44D4-1F16-4F96-8844-30F877B96109</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Government, Democracy and Justice,Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput><gtr:description>As part of my ESRC-grant &amp;quot;After the War Ends,&amp;quot; I designed and commissioned, in September 2013, a public opinion survey in the de facto state Nagorno Karabakh. The survey asks the respondents a range of questions about their perceptions of security, governance, political institutions, political participation, inter-ethnic relations, and legitimacy, which will enable me to examine how experiences of violence shape post-war attitudes. It also allows for systematic empirical research on a little-researched place. As the survey is comparable to surveys